A striking feature of the disease is its very localized occurrence. There are approximately ten small areas where it occurs, all of them more or less rural, but nothing seems to connect those areas other than the occurrence of this illness. Tanchev and colleagues suggested that the condition was ''[[sui_generis|sui generis]]''. Their initial tentative hypothesis for its cause was intoxication with [[Heavy_metal_(chemistry)|heavy metal]]s, because the affected villages were supplied with water coming from nearby [[Vratsa|Vratsa]] Mountain, a [[karst|karst]]-type mountain.

The disease was originally called "Vratsa nephritis," and became known as "Balkan endemic nephropathy" later, after people living in [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] and [[Romania|Romania]] were found to be suffering from it as well.<ref name="Tanchev & Dorossiev"/>-->

==症狀和預後==
{{seealso|腎功能|腎生理學}}

本病主要影響到的人為30歲到60歲之間。移居到流行病地區的人們直到在那裡生活了15年之後才會發病、之前不會。
